			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Runtime Support for Rule-Based Access-Control Evaluation through Model-Transformation</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/SalvadorMartínez.html">Salvador Martínez</a>, <a href="../profile/JokinGarcía.html">Jokin García</a>, <a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997375">10.1145/2997364.2997375</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The focus is runtime evaluation of access-control policies using model-based techniques.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Model transformation is used as the operational mechanism for evaluating and updating policy decisions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5a.html"><span class="tagL">T5A: Requirements</span></a><ul><li> Access-control policies are framed as enforcing security requirements (confidentiality/integrity).
</li></ul></li></ul>
